# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: beer
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] The **Eighteenth Dynasty of Egypt** (notated **Dynasty XVIII**, alternatively **18th Dynasty** or **Dynasty 18**) is classified as the first dynasty of the New Kingdom of Egypt, the era in which ancient Egypt achieved the peak of its power.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] The Eighteenth Dynasty spanned the period from 1550/1549 to 1292 BC.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] This dynasty is also known as the **Thutmoside Dynasty** for the four pharaohs named Thutmose.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] Several of Egypt's most famous pharaohs were from the Eighteenth Dynasty, including Tutankhamun (c.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] Other famous pharaohs of the dynasty include Hatshepsut (c.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] 1479 BC–1458 BC), the longest-reigning woman pharaoh of an indigenous dynasty, and Akhenaten (c.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] 1353–1336 BC), the "heretic pharaoh", with his Great Royal Wife, Nefertiti.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] The Eighteenth Dynasty is unique among indigenous Egyptian dynasties in that it had two queens regnant women who ruled as pharaohs: Hatshepsut and Neferneferuaten, usually identified as Nefertiti.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] Dynasty XVIII was founded by Ahmose I, the brother or son of Kamose, the last ruler of the 17th Dynasty.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] Ahmose finished the campaign to expel the Hyksos rulers.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] His reign is seen as the end of the Second Intermediate Period and the start of the New Kingdom.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] Ahmose's consort, Queen Ahmose-Nefertari was "arguably the most venerated woman in Egyptian history, and the grandmother of the 18th Dynasty." She was deified after she died.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] Ahmose was succeeded by his son, Amenhotep I, whose reign was relatively uneventful.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] Amenhotep I probably left no male heir and the next pharaoh, Thutmose I, seems to have been related to the royal family through marriage.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] During his reign, the borders of Egypt's empire reached their greatest expanse, extending in the north to Carchemish on the Euphrates and in the south up to Kanisah Kurgus beyond the fourth cataract of the Nile.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] Thutmose I was succeeded by Thutmose II and his queen, Hatshepsut, who was the daughter of Thutmose I.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] After her husband's death and a period of regency for her minor stepson (who would later become pharaoh as Thutmose III) Hatshepsut became pharaoh in her own right and ruled for over twenty years.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] Thutmose III, who became known as the greatest military pharaoh ever, also had a lengthy reign after becoming pharaoh.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] He had a second co-regency in his old age with his son Amenhotep II.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] Amenhotep II was succeeded by Thutmose IV, who in his turn was followed by his son Amenhotep III, whose reign is seen as a high point in this dynasty.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] Amenhotep III's reign was a period of unprecedented prosperity, artistic splendor, and international power, as attested by over 250 statues (more than any other pharaoh) and 200 large stone scarabs discovered from Syria to Nubia.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] Amenhotep III undertook large scale building programmes, the extent of which can only be compared with those of the much longer reign of Ramesses II during Dynasty XIX.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] Amenhotep III's consort was the Great Royal Wife Tiye, for whom he built an artificial lake, as described on eleven scarabs.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] Amenhotep III may have shared the throne for up to twelve years with his son Amenhotep IV.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] There is much debate about this proposed co-regency, with different experts considering that there was a lengthy co-regency, a short one, or none at all.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] In the fifth year of his reign, Amenhotep IV changed his name to Akhenaten (*ꜣḫ-n-jtn*, "Effective for the Aten") and moved his capital to Amarna, which he named Akhetaten.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] During the reign of Akhenaten, the Aten (jtn, the sun disk) became, first, the most prominent deity, and eventually came to be considered the only god.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] Whether this amounted to true monotheism continues to be the subject of debate within the academic community.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] Some state that Akhenaten created a monotheism, while others point out that he merely suppressed a dominant solar cult by the assertion of another, while he never completely abandoned several other traditional deities.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] Later Egyptians considered this "Amarna Period" an unfortunate aberration.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] After his death, Akhenaten was succeeded by two short-lived pharaohs, Smenkhkare and Neferneferuaten, of which little is known.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] In 1334 BC, Akhenaten's probable son, Tutankhaten, ascended to the throne: shortly after, he restored Egyptian polytheist cult and subsequently changed his name to Tutankhamun, in honor to the Egyptian god Amun.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] His infant daughters represent the final genetically related generation of the Eighteenth Dynasty.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] The last two members of the Eighteenth Dynasty—Ay and Horemheb—became rulers from the ranks of officials in the royal court, although Ay might also have been the maternal uncle of Akhenaten as a fellow descendant of Yuya and Tjuyu.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] Ay may have married the widowed Great Royal Wife and presumed half-sister of Tutankhamun, Ankhesenamun, in order to obtain power; she did not live long afterward, with Ay instead ascending to the throne with his long-time wife Tey, who was originally Nefertiti's wet-nurse.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] His successor was Horemheb, a general who appeared to have been Tutankhamun's heir presumptive, and whose wife Mutnedjmet might have been sister of the former queen Nefertiti.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] It is possible that Horemheb took throne away from Ay in a coup d'état.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] Although Ay's son or stepson Nakhtmin was named as his father/stepfather's Crown Prince, Nakhtmin seems to have died during the reign of Ay, leaving the opportunity for Horemheb to claim the throne next.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] Horemheb also died without surviving children, having appointed his vizier, Pa-ra-mes-su, as his heir.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] This vizier ascended the throne in 1292 BC as Ramesses I, and was the first pharaoh of the Nineteenth Dynasty.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] This example to the right depicts a man named Ay who achieved the exalted religious positions of Second Prophet of Amun and High Priest of Mut at Thebes.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] His career flourished during the reign of Tutankhamun, when the statue was made.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] The cartouches of King Ay, Tutankhamun's successor appearing on the statue, were an attempt by an artisan to "update" the sculpture.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] The Eighteenth Dynasty empire conquered all of Lower Nubia under Thutmose I.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] By the reign of Thutmose III, the Egyptians directly controlled Nubia to the Nile river, 4th cataract, with Egyptian influence / tributaries extending beyond this point.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] The Egyptians referred to the area as Kush and it was administered by the Viceroy of Kush.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] The 18th dynasty obtained Nubian gold, animal skins, ivory, ebony, cattle, and horses, which were of exceptional quality.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] The Egyptians built temples throughout Nubia.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] One of the largest and most important temples was dedicated to Amun at Jebel Barkal in the city of Napata.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] This Temple of Amun was enlarged by later Egyptian and Nubian Pharaohs, such as Taharqa.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] Radiocarbon dating suggests that Dynasty XVIII may have started a few years earlier than the conventional date of 1550 BC.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] The radiocarbon date range for its beginning is 1570–1544 BC, the mean point of which is 1557 BC.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] A 1973 X-ray examination of southern king, Seqenenre Tao, by American Egyptologists, Kent Weeks and James E.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] Harris identified cranial similarities between his cranio-facial complex along with other Nubian and Old Kingdom Giza Skulls.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] In their view, this was supportive of scholarly interpretations that Sequenre Tao and his family may have held Nubian ancestry.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] Robins and Shute (1983) performed X-ray measurements on the physical proportions of Upper Egyptian rulers such as Thutmose III, Amenhotep III, Tutankhamun.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] The authors reported that the limbs of the pharaohs, like those of other Ancient Egyptians, had "negroid characteristics", in that the distal segments were relatively long in comparison with the proximal segments.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] An exception was Ramesses II, who appears to have had short legs below the knees.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] James Harris and Fawzia Hussien (1991) conducted an X-ray survey on southern based 18th dynasty royal mummies and examined the mummified remains of Thutmose II.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] The results of the study determined that the mummy of Thutmose II had a craniofacial trait measurement that was common among Nubian populations.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] A genetic study, published in 2020, revealed Tutankhamun had the haplogroups YDNA R1b, which originated in western Asia and which today makes up 50–60% of the genetic pool of modern Europeans, and mtDNA K, which originated in the Near East.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] He shares this Y-haplogroup with his father, the KV55 mummy (Akhenaten), and grandfather, Amenhotep III (and his entire male ancestral line), and his mtDNA haplogroup with his mother, The Younger Lady, his grandmother, Tiye, and his great-grandmother, Thuya (and his entire female ancestral line).
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] The profiles for Tutankhamun and Amenhotep III were incomplete, and the analysis produced differing probability figures despite having concordant allele results.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] Because the relationships of these two mummies with the KV55 mummy had previously been confirmed in an earlier study, the haplogroup prediction of both mummies could be derived from the full profile of the KV55 data.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] Keita analysed 8 Short Tandem loci (STR) data originally published by Hawass et al. in studies from 2010 and 2012.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] The first of these studies had investigated familial relationships among 11 royal mummies of the New Kingdom, which included Tutankhamun and Amenhotep III, as well as potential inherited disorders and infectious diseases.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] The second of these studies had investigated the Y-haplogroups and genetic kinship of Ramesses III and an unknown man buried along with him in the royal cache at Deir el Bahari.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] Keita analysed the STR data from these studies using an algorithm that only has three choices: Eurasians, sub-Saharan Africans, and East Asians.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] Using these three options, Keita concluded that the majority of the samples had a population "affinity with 'sub-Saharan' Africans in one affinity analysis".
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] However, Keita cautioned that this does not mean that the royal mummies "lacked other affiliations", which he argued had been obscured in typological thinking.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] Keita further added that different "data and algorithms might give different results", reflecting the complexity of biological heritage and the associated interpretation.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] According to historian William Stiebling and archaeologist Susan N.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] Helft, (2023) conflicting DNA analysis on recent genetic samples such as the Amarna royal mummies has led to a lack of consensus on the genetic makeup of the ancient Egyptians and their geographic origins.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] In 2025, biochemist Jean-Philippe Gourdine reviewed genetic data on the Ancient Egyptian populations in the international scholarly publication, General History of Africa Volume IX.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] In 2025, Christopher Ehret, David Schoenbrun, Steven A Brandt and Shomarka Keita issued a multidisciplinary review, noting the R1b M89 haplogroup subtype identified among the three Amarna pharaohs (Tutankhamun, Amenhotep III and Akhenaten) was not further specified.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] The authors also stated that the R1b haplogroup usually interpreted as indicating a back migration to Africa from or via the Near East could have been attributed to Asian back migration or trans-Saharan connections as the genetic marker is found at relative high frequencies among Chadic populations.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] Referencing a Short Tandem Report (STR) autosomal background analysis on the Amarna royal mummies, performed by Keita in an earlier publication, the authors considered this analysis could suggest closer trans-Saharan connections.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] Ehret et al also disclosed through personal communication with the Gad team that "other eighteenth dynasty lineages in the Amarna period were found to be E1b1a (Gad et al 2020)".
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] The authors further postulated that association of the palaeolithic Asian lineage (R1B) and an affiliation that is tropical African (E1b1a) is an example of admixture found in some Nile Valley populations, and that a mixture of lineages could illustrate Egypt being near a crossroads.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] The pharaohs of the 18th Dynasty ruled for approximately 250 years (c.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] The dates and names in the table are taken from Dodson and Hilton.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] Many of the pharaohs were buried in the Valley of the Kings in Thebes (designated KV).
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] More information can be found on the Theban Mapping Project website.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] Several diplomatic marriages are known for the New Kingdom.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] These daughters of foreign kings are often only mentioned in cuneiform texts and are not known from other sources.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] The marriages were likely to have been a way to confirm good relations between these states.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] Royal brother-sister marriages were observed, as a means to strengthen the royalty by echoing the practices in their creation myths.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] The Eighteenth Dynasty is well-recorded across Egyptian king lists, mostly due to being written extensively by their Nineteenth Dynasty successors.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] A Theban tomb, TT19, also provides a king list.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] It's possible the Turin King List originally listed the Eighteenth Dynasty, but it's now in a fragmentary state and some information is lost, including a section that contained Dynasties 18–19/20.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] Manetho's now-lost work *Aegyptiaca* also provided individual reign lengths, however the lengths seem to be inaccurate since his sources were likely already corrupted due to the *damnatio memoriae* imposed over the Amarna rulers, and co-regency may have caused additional confusion.
[src:beer/18th-dynasty] Later Epitomes of the work were then misunderstood by various writers who conflated multiple kings into a single figure, failed to understand the number of kings in this dynasty.
[src:beer/2m2b] Historically, TAA has been used as an anesthetic and more recently as a recreational drug.
[src:beer/2m2b] TAA is mostly a positive allosteric modulator for GABAA receptors in the same way as ethanol.
[src:beer/2m2b] The psychotropic effects of TAA and ethanol are similar, though distinct.
[src:beer/2m2b] Impact on coordination and balance are proportionately more prominent with TAA, which is significantly more potent by weight than ethanol.
[src:beer/2m2b] Its appeal as an alternative to ethanol may stem from its lack of a hangover (due to different metabolic pathways) and the fact that it is often not detected on standard drug test.
[src:beer/2m2b] TAA is a colorless liquid with a burning flavor and an unpleasant odor similar to paraldehyde with a hint of camphor.
[src:beer/2m2b] TAA remains liquid at room temperature, making it a useful alternative solvent to *tert*-butyl alcohol.
[src:beer/2m2b] TAA is primarily made by the hydration of 2-methyl-2-butene in the presence of an acidic catalyst.
[src:beer/2m2b] Fusel alcohols like TAA are grain fermentation byproducts, and therefore trace amounts of TAA are present in many alcoholic beverages.
[src:beer/2m2b] Traces of TAA have been detected in other foods, like fried bacon, cassava and rooibos tea.
[src:beer/2m2b] TAA is also present in rabbit milk and seems to play a role in pheromone-inducing suckling in the newborn rabbit.
[src:beer/2m2b] From about the 1880s to the 1950s, TAA was used as an anesthetic with the contemporary name of *amylene hydrate*, but it was rarely used because more efficient drugs existed.
[src:beer/2m2b] In the 1930s, TAA was mainly used as a solvent for the primary anesthetic tribromoethanol (TBE).
[src:beer/2m2b] Like chloroform, TBE is toxic for the liver, so the use of such solutions declined in the 1940s in humans.
[src:beer/2m2b] TBE-TAA-solutions remained in use as short-acting anesthetics for laboratory mice and rats.
[src:beer/2m2b] Such solutions are sometimes called *Avertin*, which was a brand name for the now discontinued TAA and TBE solution with a volume ratio of 0.5:1 made by Winthrop Laboratories.
[src:beer/2m2b] TAA has emerged recently as a recreational drug.
[src:beer/2m2b] Ingestion or inhalation of TAA causes euphoria, sedative, hypnotic, and anticonvulsant effects similar to ethanol.
[src:beer/2m2b] When ingested, the effects of TAA may begin in about 30 minutes and can last up to 1–2 days.
[src:beer/2m2b] 2–4 grams of TAA is sufficient to produce a hypnotic effect.
[src:beer/2m2b] About 100 g of ethanol induces a similar level of sedation.
[src:beer/2m2b] The smallest known dose of TAA that has killed a person is 30 mL.
[src:beer/2m2b] An overdose produces symptoms similar to alcohol poisoning and is a medical emergency due to the sedative/depressant properties which manifest in overdose as potentially lethal respiratory depression.
[src:beer/2m2b] Sudden loss of consciousness, simultaneous respiratory and metabolic acidosis, fast heartbeat, increased blood pressure, pupil constriction, coma, respiratory depression and death may follow from an overdose.
[src:beer/2m2b] The subcutaneous LD50 in mice is 2.1 g/kg.
[src:beer/2m2b] In rats, TAA is primarily metabolized via glucuronidation, as well as by oxidation to 2-methyl-2,3-butanediol.
[src:beer/2m2b] It is likely that the same path is followed in humans, though older sources suggest TAA is excreted unchanged.
[src:beer/2m2b] The use of TAA cannot be detected with general ethanol tests or other ordinary drug tests.
[src:beer/2m2b] Its use can be detected from a blood or a urine sample by using gas chromatography–mass spectrometry for up to 48 hours after consumption.
[src:beer/4-hydroxyphenylacetic-acid] 4-Hydroxyphenylacetic acid is obtained by reducing 4-hydroxymandelic acid with elemental phosphorus and iodine.
[src:beer/4-hydroxyphenylacetic-acid] In industry, 4-hydroxyphenylacetic acid is an intermediate to atenolol, 3,4-dihydroxyphenylacetic acid, and coclaurine.
[src:beer/8-prenylnaringenin] 8-PN is found in hops (*Humulus lupulus*) and in beer, and is responsible for the estrogenic effects of the former.
[src:beer/8-prenylnaringenin] It can be produced from isoxanthohumol in fungal cells cultures, and by flora in the human intestine.
[src:beer/8-prenylnaringenin] 8-PN was shown to preserve bone density and has been demonstrated to reduce hot flashes.
[src:beer/8-prenylnaringenin] 8-PN also induces the secretion of prolactin, and increases other estrogenic responses.
[src:beer/8-prenylnaringenin] The compound binds to and activates ERα more times than it does to ERβ.
[src:beer/8-prenylnaringenin] This prenylflavanoid has drawn interest in the study of hormone replacement therapy, and it is comparable to some selective estrogen-receptor modulators.
[src:beer/8-prenylnaringenin] In an in vivo study, 8-PN has activated proliferation of mammary cells.
[src:beer/8-prenylnaringenin] At the concentration found in beer, it is unlikely to have an estrogenic effect in breast tissue.
[src:beer/8-prenylnaringenin] Similar to other estrogens, 8-PN induces the expression of the progesterone receptor in various tissues.
[src:beer/8-prenylnaringenin] Luteinizing hormone (LH) and follicle stimulating hormone (FSH) are suppressed by 8-PN, indicating that it possesses antigonadotropic properties.
[src:beer/8-prenylnaringenin] The role 8-PN plays in fertility requires further research.
[src:beer/8-prenylnaringenin] In an *in vitro* study, 8-PN and synthetic derivatives demonstrated anticancer properties.
[src:beer/8-prenylnaringenin] Prenylflavonoids from hops, including 8-PN, are ingredients in some breast enlargement supplements, though there is no evidence of its effectiveness for this purpose.
[src:beer/8-prenylnaringenin] The enzyme naringenin 8-dimethylallyltransferase uses dimethylallyl diphosphate and (−)-(2S)-naringenin to produce diphosphate and sophoraflavanone B (8-prenylnaringenin).
[src:beer/8-prenylnaringenin] The enzyme 8-dimethylallylnaringenin 2'-hydroxylase uses sophoraflavanone B (8-prenylnaringenin), NADPH, H+ and O2 to produce leachianone G, NADP+ and H2O.
[src:beer/8-prenylnaringenin] Synthesized derivatives of 8-PN are: 7,4′-di-O-methyl-8-prenylnaringenin; 7-O-pentyl-8-prenylnaringenin; 7,4′-Di-O-allyl-8-prenylnaringenin; 7,4′-Di-O-acetyl-8-prenylnaringenin; and 7,4′-Di-O-palmitoyl-8-prenylnaringenin.
[src:beer/8-prenylnaringenin] 8-Neopentylnaringenin and 8-n-heptylnaringenin are synthetic derivatives of 8-PN.
[src:beer/8-prenylnaringenin] There is another compound, 8-isopentenylnaringenin, also known as sophoraflavanone B, from *Sophora flavescens*, that could properly be called 8-prenylnaringenin by scientific naming convention.
[src:beer/abbess] An **abbess** (Latin: *abbatissa*) is the female superior of a community of nuns in an abbey.
[src:beer/abbess] In the Catholic Church (both the Latin Church and Eastern Catholic), Eastern Orthodox, Coptic, Lutheran and Anglican abbeys, the mode of election, position, rights, and authority of an abbess correspond generally with those of an abbot.
[src:beer/abbess] She must be at least 40 years old and have been a nun for 10 years.
[src:beer/abbess] The age requirement in the Catholic Church has evolved over time, ranging from 30 to 60.
[src:beer/abbess] In the rare case of there not being a nun with the qualifications, the requirements may be lowered to 30 years of age and five of those in an "upright manner", as determined by the superior.
[src:beer/abbess] A woman who is of illegitimate birth, is not a virgin, has undergone non-salutory public penance, is a widow, or is blind or deaf, is typically disqualified for the position, saving by permission of the Holy See.
[src:beer/abbess] The office is elective, the choice being by the secret votes of the nuns belonging to the community.
[src:beer/abbess] Like an abbot, after being confirmed in her office by the Holy See, an abbess is solemnly admitted to her office by a formal blessing, conferred by the bishop in whose territory the monastery is located, or by an abbot or another bishop with appropriate permission.
[src:beer/abbess] Unlike the abbot, the abbess receives only the ring, the crosier, and a copy of the rule of the order.
[src:beer/abbess] She does not receive a mitre as part of the ceremony.
[src:beer/abbess] The abbess also traditionally adds a pectoral cross to the outside of her habit as a symbol of office, though she continues to wear a modified form of her religious habit or dress, as she is unordained—females cannot be ordained—and so does not vest or use choir dress in the liturgy.
[src:beer/abbess] An abbess serves for life, except in Italy and some adjacent islands.
[src:beer/abbess] They have full authority in its administration.
[src:beer/abbess] However, there are significant limitations.
[src:beer/abbess] There are exigent circumstances, where due to Apostolical privilege, certain abbesses have been granted rights and responsibilities above the normal, such as the abbess of the Cistercian Monastery of the Abbey of Santa María la Real de Las Huelgas near Burgos, Spain.
[src:beer/abbess] Also granted exceptional rights was the abbess of the Cistercian order in Conversano, Italy.
[src:beer/abbess] She was granted the ability to appoint her own vicar-general, select and approve the confessors, along with the practice of receiving the public homage of her clergy.
[src:beer/abbess] This practice continued until some of the duties were modified due to an appeal by the clergy to Rome.
[src:beer/abbess] Finally in 1750, the public homage was abolished.
[src:beer/abbess] During the Middle Ages (7th–10th centuries) in the Catholic Church, greater restrictions on abbesses' spiritual independence gained pace.
[src:beer/abbess] Instruments of church authority, from papal bulls down to local sanctions, were increasingly used to restrict their freedom to dispense blessings, administer sacraments, including the veiling of nuns, and publicly read the gospels or preach.
[src:beer/abbess] Such spiritual—and even temporal—authority had in earlier church history, largely been unremarkable.
[src:beer/abbess] As Thomas Oestereich, contributor to the *Catholic Encyclopedia* (1913), makes clear, abbesses' past spiritual authority was increasingly seen as the "usurpation" of corresponding priestly power, and a solely male privilege.
[src:beer/abbess] Historically, in some Celtic monasteries, abbesses presided over joint-houses of monks and nuns, the most famous example being Saint Brigid of Kildare's leadership in the founding of the monastery at Kildare in Ireland.
[src:beer/abbess] This custom accompanied Celtic monastic missions to France, Spain, and even to Rome itself.
[src:beer/abbess] In 1115, Robert, the founder of Fontevraud Abbey near Chinon and Saumur, France, committed the government of the whole order, men as well as women, to a female superior.
[src:beer/abbess] In Lutheran churches, the title of abbess (German: *Äbtissin*) has in some cases survived (for example, in the Itzehoe Convent to designate the heads of abbeys which since the Protestant Reformation have continued as monasteries or convents (German: *Stifte*).
[src:beer/abbess] These positions continued, merely changing from Catholic to Lutheran.
[src:beer/abbess] The first to make this change was the Abbey of Quedlinburg, whose last Catholic abbess died in 1514.
[src:beer/abbess] These are collegiate foundations, which provide a home and an income for unmarried ladies, generally of noble birth, called canonesses (German: *Kanonissinen*), or more usually, *Stiftsdamen* or *Kapitularinnen*.
[src:beer/abbess] The office of abbess is of considerable social dignity, and in the past, was sometimes filled by princesses of the reigning houses.
[src:beer/abbess] Until the dissolution of Holy Roman Empire and mediatisation of smaller imperial fiefs by Napoleon, the evangelical abbess of Quedlinburg was also per officio the head of that *reichsunmittelbar* state.
[src:beer/abbess] The last such ruling abbess was Sofia Albertina, Princess of Sweden.
[src:beer/abbess] The abess Hildegard of Fraunmünster Abbey sat in the Imperial Diet among other princes of the Holy Roman Empire.
[src:beer/abbess] The oldest women's abbey in Germany is St.
[src:beer/abbess] Marienthal Abbey of Cistercian nuns, near Ostritz, established during the early 13th century.
[src:beer/abbess] In the Hradčany of Prague is a Catholic institute whose mistress is titled an abbess.
[src:beer/abbess] It was founded in 1755 by the Empress Maria Theresa, and traditionally was responsible for the coronation of the Queen of Bohemia.
[src:beer/abbess] The abbess is required to be an Austrian archduchess.
[src:beer/abbess] In 1997, it was estimated the Catholic Church had around 200 presiding abbesses.
[src:beer/abbess] The word 'Abbas' is used as part of a place name (for example, the English villages of Compton Abbas and Milton Abbas).
[src:beer/abbess] The name usually relates to land previously owned by an abbess.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] In 2016, UNESCO inscribed Belgian beer culture on their list of the intangible cultural heritage of humanity.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] In Belgium, beer was already produced in the Roman era, as evidenced by the excavation of a brewery and malthouse from the 3rd and 4th centuries AD at Ronchinne.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] During the Early and High Middle Ages, beer was produced with gruit, a mix of herbs and spices that was first mentioned in 974 when the bishop of Liège was granted the right to sell it at Fosses-la-Ville.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] From the 14th century onwards, gruit was replaced by hops, after the example of imported beers from northern Germany and Holland.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] After that, several Belgian towns developed their own types of beer for export to other regions, most notably the white beer of Leuven and Hoegaarden, the *caves* of Lier and the *uitzet* of Ghent.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] In recent years, the use of gruit has experienced a revival, particularly among homebrewers and eventually by commercial breweries.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] For instance, Gageleer brews a beer using sweet gale (*Myrica gale*) based on a medieval recipe.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Monasteries played only a small role in beer production and mostly brewed for their own consumption and that of their guests.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Monastic brewing would only receive some renown from the late 19th century onwards, when the Trappists of Chimay produced a brown beer that was commercially available.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] In 1885, a change in legislation made brewing of German-style bottom-fermenting beers viable in Belgium, and it was only from then that large industrial-scale brewing in Belgium took off.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] During the 20th century the number of breweries in Belgium declined from 3223 breweries in 1900 to only 106 breweries in 1993.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Yet, a number of traditional beer styles, such as white beer, lambic and Flemish old brown were preserved, while new local, top-fermented styles developed, such as *spéciale belge*, abbey beer and Belgian strong ale.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] In 1988, the country's two biggest breweries, Artois and Piedboeuf, formally merged to become Interbrew, then the world's 18th biggest brewer, which was to merge with AmBev in 2004 to become today's AB InBev, the biggest beer producing company in the world.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] In Belgium, four types of fermentation methods are used for the brewing of beer, which is unique in the world.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Belgian beers have a range of colours, brewing methods, and alcohol levels.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Beers brewed in Trappist monasteries are termed Trappist beers.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] For a beer to qualify for Trappist certification, the brewery must be in a monastery, the monks must play a role in its production and the policies and the profits from the sale must be used to support the monastery or social programs outside.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Only ten monasteries currently meet these qualifications, five of which are in Belgium, two in the Netherlands, one in Austria, one in Italy and one in the United Kingdom.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Trappist beer is a controlled term of origin: it tells where the beers come from, it is not the name of a beer style.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Beyond their being mostly warm fermented, Trappist beers have very little in common stylistically.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] In addition to the above, a lower-strength beer is sometimes brewed for consumption by the brothers (*patersbier*) or sold on site.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] For example, *l’Orval Vert* (or *Petit Orval*, also known as "Green Orval" or "Small Orval") is served to the monks and guests of the Orval Abbey and can only be consumed on tap in the nearby *À l’Ange Gardien* abbey café.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] The designation "abbey beers" (*Bières d'Abbaye* or *Abdijbier*) originally applied to any monastic or monastic-style beer.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] After introduction of an official Trappist beer designation by the International Trappist Association in 1997, it came to mean products similar in style or presentation to monastic beers.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] The requirements for registration under the logo include the monastery having control over certain aspects of the commercial operation, and a proportion of profits going to the abbey or to its designated charities.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Monastic orders other than the Trappists can be and are included in this arrangement.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] The "Abbey beer" logo and quality label is no longer used for beers given the name of a fictitious abbey, a vaguely monastic branding or a saint name without mentioning a specific monastery.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Some brewers may produce abbey-style beers such as dubbel or tripel, using such names but will refrain from using the term Abbey beer in their branding.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] What connoisseurs now recognize as Trappist breweries began operations in 1838.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Several monasteries, however, maintained "working" breweries for 500+ years before the French regime disrupted religious life (1795–1799).
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Even then, some Abbey beers such as Affligem Abbey, whose name now appears on beers made by the Heineken-owned Affligem Brewery, resumed brewing from "working" monasteries until the occupation of most of Belgium in World War I.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Commercial Abbey beers first appeared during Belgium's World War I recovery.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Although Abbey beers do not conform to rigid brewing styles, most tend to include the most recognizable and distinctive Trappist styles of brune (Belgian brown ale, aka dubbel), strong pale ale or tripel, and blonde ale or blond.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Modern abbey breweries range from microbreweries to international giants, but at least one beer writer warns against assuming that closeness of connection with a real monastery confirms a product's quality.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] This style makes up the bulk of beer production and consumption in Belgium.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Belgian Pilsners are not particularly distinctive or renowned by connoisseurs.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] The top brands include Jupiler (within Belgium) and Stella Artois (both brewed by Inbev), Maes pils and Cristal (both brewed by the Alken Maes branch of Heineken).
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Stella Artois, originating in Leuven, Belgium; is distributed globally.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] The Pilsnerbeer is which is popularly called "*pintje*" (in Flemish, from English "pint" but in volume only 0.25 cl or roughly 1/2 pint) or "*choppe*" (in French) in Belgium, was the basis of the "*fluitjesbier*" distributed during the German occupation in WWII and under rationing.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] This "*fluitjesbier*" was watered down to about 0.8° (compared to fruitjuice which can have up to 1.5° due to natural fermentation).
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Bock is a strong lager of German origin.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Some Belgian brewers have produced bock-style beers what makes it a style applicable to Belgium.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] This type of beer, commonly called *witbier* in Dutch, *bière blanche* in French and *wheat beer* in English, originated in the Flemish part of Belgium in the Middle Ages.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Traditionally, it is made with a mixture of wheat and barley.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Before hops became widely available in Europe, beers were flavoured with a mixture of herbs called gruit.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] In the later years of the Middle Ages, hops were added to the gruit.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] That mixture continues today in most Belgian white beers.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] The production of this type of beer in Belgium had nearly ended by the late 1950s.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] In the town of Hoegaarden, the last *witbier* brewery, Tomsin, closed its doors in 1955.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] However, ten years later, a young farmer by the name of Pierre Celis in the same village decided to try reviving the beer.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] In 1966, Celis began brewing a "witbier" in his farmhouse.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Ultimately, the Hoegaarden brewery took the name of the village and became successful, gaining international prominence.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] For instance, in 2018, only 8% of the 1.3 million hectoliters of beer produced annually were intended for the Belgian market.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Some notable current examples are Celis White, Blanche de Namur and Watou's Wit.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Their alcohol strength is about 5–6 percent ABV, and these beers can be quite refreshing, especially during the warm summer months.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] The herb mixture traditionally includes coriander and bitter orange peel, among other herbs.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] White beers also have a moderate light grain sweetness from the wheat used.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] In recent times, brewers have been making fruit flavoured wheat beers.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] These are a light variation on pale ale, often made with pilsner malt.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Some beer writers regard blonde and golden ales as distinct styles, while others do not.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Duvel is the archetypal Belgian blonde ale, and one of the most popular bottled beers in the country as well as being well known internationally.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Its name means "Devil" and some other blonde beers follow the theme—Satan, Lucifer and Judas for example.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] The style is popular with Walloon brewers, the slightly hazy Moinette being the best-known example.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Chouffe can be considered a spiced version (with coriander).
[src:beer/abbey-beers] A few Belgian beers are pale and assertively hopped.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] De Ranke's XX Bitter has a British-style name.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Arabier from De Dolle Brouwers.Brouwerij Van Eecke's Poperings Hommelbier, another example, hails from Belgium's hop-growing district.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] From Lambic four kinds of beer are produced: Lambic, Gueuze, Fruit Lambic, and Faro.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] These are beers similar to the traditional pale ales of England, although less bitterly hopped.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] A notable example is the 5% ABV De Koninck brand, with its distinctive half-spherical glasses (called 'bollekes').
[src:beer/abbey-beers] It is popular in its native city of Antwerp.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Some, such as Vieux Temps, were based on British styles to please troops stationed in Belgium during World War I.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Others were introduced by the UK-born brewer George Maw Johnson in the late 19th century.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] A very strong *ambrée* is brewed by "Bush" (*Dubuisson*), another brewery influenced by British styles.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Walloon amber or *ambrée* ale, such a Gauloise Ambrée, is considered to be somewhat distinct by some beer writers, and to be influenced by the French version of the *ambrée* style.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Tripel is a term used originally by brewers in the Low Countries to describe a strong pale ale, and became associated with *Westmalle Tripel*.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] The style of Westmalle's *Tripel* and the name was widely copied by the breweries of Belgium, then the term spread to the US and other countries.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] *Gulden Draak* was awarded the best-tasting beer in the world in 1998 by the *American Tasting Institute* (now ChefsBest).
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Dubbel (*double*) has a characteristic brown colour.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] It is one of the classic Abbey/Trappist types, having been developed in the 19th century at the Trappist monastery in Westmalle.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Today, some commercial brewers using abbey names call their strong brown beers "Dubbel".
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Typically, a dubbel is between 6 and 8% abv.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] In addition to the dubbels made by most Trappist breweries, examples include St.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Bernardus Pater, Adelardus Dubbel, Maredsous 8 and Witkap Dubbel.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Dubbels are characteristically bottle conditioned.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] The result is a mildly strong 'drinking' beer with a deep reddish-brown colour and a distinctly acidic, sour yet fruity and mouthy taste.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] This style is closely related to Oud bruin.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] This style, aged in wooden casks, is a cousin to the sour "Flemish Red" style.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Examples include Rodenbach, Goudenband and Petrus.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Regular bruin or brune beers such as Grottenbier are darker than amber ales, less sour than Flemish brown ale, and less strong than dubbel.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] These sweet, heavy-bodied brown ales represent a style which originated in the British Isles.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] The Caledonian theme is usually heavily emphasized with tartan and thistles appearing on labels.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Examples include Gordon's, Scotch de Silly and La Chouffe Mc Chouffe.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Belgian stouts subdivide into sweeter and drier, and stronger and weaker versions.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Examples include Callewaerts and Ellezelloise Hercule.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] The sweeter versions resemble the almost-defunct British style "milk stout", while the stronger ones are sometimes described as Imperial stouts.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Champagne style beers are generally ales that are finished "à la méthode originale" for champagne.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Examples include Grottenbier, DeuS and Malheur Bière Brut.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] They receive a second fermentation much like Champagne does and are stored for several months "sûr lie" while the fermentation lasts.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] This creates the smaller, softer bubbles that we know from Champagne, but maintains the beer flavour and style.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] In Belgium "Grand Cru" is more often used than "Quadrupel", these beers are a mostly a blend of brews, which is often refermented as a blend.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Saison (French for "season") is the name originally given to refreshing, low-alcohol beers brewed seasonally in Wallonia, the French-speaking region of Belgium.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] First seen in early 19th century Liège, saisons gained notoriety as a luxury beer in 20th century Hainaut brewed by city and countryside brewers alike.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] By the 1980s, they were only produced on the countryside.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Modern-day saisons are also brewed in other countries, particularly USA, and are generally bottle conditioned, with an average range of 5 to 8% ABV, though saisons at the more traditional 3.5% strength can still be found.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Although saison has been described as an endangered style, there has been a rise in interest in this style in recent years, with Saison Dupont being named "the Best Beer in the World" by the magazine *Men's Journal* in July 2005.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] A related style known as a grisette was brewed with a lower ABV and with wheat added.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Many breweries produce special beers during December.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Most contain more alcohol than the brewery's other types of beer and may also contain spicing.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] An annual beer festival in Essen near Antwerp focuses on this type of beer with over 190 beers available for tasting in 2014.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Some brewers that are not Lambic-brewers make fruit beers in a similar process as the Fruit Lambic beers.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] All brewers of this style make fruit lambic.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Many brewers of top fermentation beers such as Belgian golden ales, ambers and Flemish old brown beers, that produce beers that usually go through a multiple stage fermentation process, are catching on to the trend to make fruit beers.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] The process starts after the first fermentation of the wort, when sometimes sugar is added to referment the beer on wooden casks.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] To make fruit beer the fruit, juice or syrup is added (instead of sugar) to the first brew and refermented, these may be termed fruit lambics or fruit beers, depending on the type of first brew.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Beer that has fruit syrup or fruit lemonade added after (the final stage of) fermentation, in other words as a flavouring, are termed "Radlers" ("Shandy" in the UK) definitely not fruit beer.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Beers above 7%, such as tripels or strong dubbels, are referred to in some sources as Belgian strong ale, although this is not a name used by Belgian brewers.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Belgian beers have a wide range of styles and brewing methods and are almost always served in unique, branded glassware.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Each glass is designed to enhance the beer’s taste and aroma, often featuring the brewery’s logo or a beer-specific design.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Belgian "heavy" or "special" beers (stronger or bottled beers) are usually served in more elaborate branded beer glassware.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Some glasses are etched on the bottom; typically with the brewery’s logo, to nucleate a stream of bubbles for maintaining a nice head.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Unless the bar is out of the specific glass that goes with that beer it is usually served in its own glass.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Most bartenders or waitresses will apologize if the beer comes in a different glass.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Pils (pilsner) or pale lager, remains the most widely produced and consumed beer style in Belgium.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] One of the most typical Belgian pilsner glasses is the ribbed glass, often referred to as the *ribbelke* or *ribbelglas*.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] The Belgian pilsner glass originated between 1860 and 1900.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Its ribbed base was designed to minimize heat transfer from the drinker’s hand, preventing the beer from warming.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Additionally, the glass’s tall, narrow, and straight shape is suited to pilsner beers due to their lower foaming protein content, necessitating a smaller diameter to maintain an appropriate head.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] A regional variation is the *Boerke* glass, which translates to "small farmer".
[src:beer/abbey-beers] The question of which glass is best suited for Belgian pilsner remains a subject of debate, influenced by factors such as personal preference, brand loyalty, tradition, regional customs, and differing opinions among Belgians.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] One of the more common types is the tulip glass.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] A tulip glass not only helps trap the aroma, but also aids in maintaining large heads, creating a visual and olfactory sensation.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] The body is bulbous, but the top flares out to form a lip which helps foam head retention.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] A vessel similar to a champagne flute is the preferred serving vessel for Belgian (fruit) Lambics, Gueuze and fruit beers.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] The narrow shape helps maintain carbonation, while providing a strong aromatic front.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Flute glasses display the lively carbonation, sparkling colour, and soft lacing of this distinct style.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Traditionally, lambic beers including gueuze and fruit lambics are served in a tall glass resembling the ribbed pilsner glass.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] However, the edges and base of the lambic glass are significantly thicker; which originated from the old custom of grinding sugar at the bottom of the glass before serving, allowing drinkers to sweeten the beer to their taste, as lambic styles are known for their intense sourness.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] The glass is commonly referred to as a *lambiekstoemper* (or "lambic stomper"), a name that reflects the practice of crushing sugar with a tool similar to a cocktail muddler.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Chalices and goblets are large, stemmed, bowl-shaped glasses mainly associated with Trappist and Abbey ales.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] The distinction between goblet and chalice is typically in the glass thickness.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Goblets tend to be more delicate and thin, while the chalice is heavy and thick walled.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] However, a more recent addition, though not traditionally Belgian, is the TeKu beer glass, developed in 2006 by Teo Musso and Kuaska (hence the acronym).
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Designed as a universal beer glass, it has since been embraced by the craft beer community, particularly for styles such as pale ales, IPAs, stouts...
[src:beer/abbey-beers] In addition to the profusion of glasses provided by brewers, some Belgian beer cafés serve beer in their own "house" glassware.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] The majority of Belgian beer brands are sold in reusable bottles.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Draught beers tend mostly to be pale lagers, wheat beers, regional favourites such as kriek in Brussels or De Koninck in Antwerp; and the occasional one-off.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] These days, Belgian beers are sold in brown- (or sometimes dark green-) tinted glass bottles (to avoid negative effects of light on the beverage) and sealed with a cork, a metal crown cap, or sometimes both.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Some beers are bottle conditioned, meaning reseeded with yeast so that an additional fermentation may take place.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Different bottle sizes exist: 25 cl, 33 cl, 37.5 cl, 75 cl and multiples of 75.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] (8, 12, 24 or multiples of 24 fl. oz.) The 37.5 cl size is usually for lambics.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Other beers are generally bottled in 25 or 33 cl format (depending on brands).
[src:beer/abbey-beers] The bigger bottles (75 cl) are sold almost in every food shop but customers do not always have an extensive choice.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Bottles larger than 75 cl are named following the terminology used for champagne and are limited in quantity.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] In Brussels or Walloon Belgian cafés, you can order orders a *demi* (English: "half"), which is a 50 cl draught beer.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] The prominence of the Belgian beer culture is reflected in the extensive range of beers offered in nearly every café across the country.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Belgium contains thousands of cafés that offer a wide selection of beers, a typical beer menu ranges from at least half a dozen draught beers and two dozen bottled beers of different types in a neighborhood café, to over 1000 in a specialist beer café.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Although many major brands of beer are available at most supermarkets, off-licences located throughout the country generally offer a far wider selection, albeit at somewhat higher prices.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] In 2024, Belgium exported around 70% of its beer production, amounting to approximately 14 million hectoliters.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Some draught-beer brands produced by AB InBev like Stella Artois, Hoegaarden and Leffe are available in several European countries.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Aside from these, mostly bottled beer is exported across Europe.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Cafés, exclusively or primarily offering Belgian beers, exist beyond Belgium in Australia, New Zealand, Canada, France, the United Kingdom and the United States, amongst others.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Some beer festivals outside Belgium have a Belgian beer bar as an alternative to local products.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] In North America, a growing number of draught Belgian beer brands have started to become available, often at "Belgian Bars".
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Such brands include Brasserie Brunehaut, Karmeliet, Kwak, Maredsous, Mont Saint-Aubert, Delirium, Palm, Rodenbach and St.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] A number of traditional Belgian dishes use beer as an ingredient.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] One is *carbonade* (French) or *stoverij* or *stoofvlees* (Dutch), a stew of beef cooked in beer, similar to Boeuf bourguignon.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] The beer used is typically the regional speciality—lambic in Brussels, De Koninck in Antwerp, and so on—so that the taste of the dish varies.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] *In't Spinnekopke*, Brussels, and *Den Dyver*, Bruges are famed for their beer cookery.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] In 1998 Anheuser-Busch InBev started a worldwide chain of bars/restaurants, Belgian Beer Cafe, serving typical Belgian dishes combined with Belgian Beer.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Beer writers who have written extensively on Belgian beer include Belgians Peter Crombeq, Gert van Lierde and Erik Verdonck, and Britons Michael Jackson and Tim Webb.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] The following list contains beers that are brewed in Belgium.
[src:beer/abbey-beers] Not to be confused with "Belgian style" beers that are produced in other countries, and may or may not resemble a style that is specific to Belgium.
[src:beer/absinth-wormwood] Wormwood's relative mugwort was traditionally used as a remedy for a variety of complaints, especially those of a gynaecological nature, and so the wormwood genus bears the name of the Greek goddess of childbirth, Artemis.
[src:beer/absinth-wormwood] The specific name derives from *apsínthion*, the Greek term for the plant.
[src:beer/absinth-wormwood] "Wormwood" itself is an alteration of Old English *wermod*, which is of obscure origin.
[src:beer/absinth-wormwood] The German cognate *Wermut* is the source of the term vermouth, used in French and English to describe a kind of wine traditionally flavoured with wormwood.
[src:beer/absinth-wormwood] Leaves are spirally arranged, greenish-grey colored above, white below, covered with silky silvery-white trichomes, and bearing minute oil-producing glands.
[src:beer/absinth-wormwood] The basal leaves are up to 250 mm (10 in) long, bi- to tripinnate with long petioles, with the cauline leaves (those on the stem) smaller, 50–100 mm (2–4 in) long, less divided, and with short petioles.
[src:beer/absinth-wormwood] The uppermost leaves can be both simple and sessile (without a petiole).
[src:beer/absinth-wormwood] Flowers are pale yellow, tubular, and clustered in spherical bent-down heads (capitula), which are in turn clustered in leafy and branched panicles.
[src:beer/absinth-wormwood] Flowering occurs from early summer to early autumn; pollination is anemophilous.
[src:beer/absinth-wormwood] The plant can easily be cultivated in dry soil.
[src:beer/absinth-wormwood] It should be planted under bright exposure in fertile, midweight soil.
[src:beer/absinth-wormwood] It prefers soil rich in nitrogen, and can be propagated by ripened cuttings taken in spring or autumn in temperate climates, or by seeds in nursery beds.
[src:beer/absinth-wormwood] Growing the plant with others tends to stunt their growth; accordingly, it is not considered to be a good companion plant.
[src:beer/absinth-wormwood] *A. absinthium* also self-seeds generously.
[src:beer/absinth-wormwood] It is naturalised in some areas away from its native range, including much of North America and the Kashmir Valley of India.
[src:beer/absinth-wormwood] This plant, and its cultivars "Lambrook Mist" and "Lambrook Silver" have gained the Royal Horticultural Society's Award of Garden Merit.
[src:beer/absinth-wormwood] These two short cultivars are very similar and more silver than typical British absinthium material and probably derive from southern Europe.
[src:beer/absinth-wormwood] "Lambrook Silver" is the earliest of these cultivars, having been selected in the late 1950s by Margery Fish, who developed the garden at East Lambrook Manor.
[src:beer/absinth-wormwood] "Lambrook Mist" was selected about 30 years later by Andrew Norton, a subsequent owner of the garden.
[src:beer/absinth-wormwood] Both gained their Awards of Garden Merit during the RHS Artemisia Trial 1991–3.
[src:beer/absinth-wormwood] Cultivar "Silver Ghost" is a taller, silver plant, which flowers much later (August–September) than typical absinthium (June–July) in Britain, and so holds its silver appearance for longer.
[src:beer/absinth-wormwood] This and a more feathery-leaved cultivar "Persian Lace" were selected by National Collection Holder John Twibell in the 1990s.
[src:beer/absinth-wormwood] Wormwood herb contains bitter substances from the group of sesquiterpene lactones; absinthin, at 0.20 to 0.28%, is the main component of these bitter substances.
[src:beer/absinth-wormwood] Essential oils make up 0.2 to 0.8% and contain (-) - thujone, (+) - isothujone, thujyl alcohol and its esters, chamazulene and other mono- and sesquiterpenes.
[src:beer/absinth-wormwood] In Bailen et al 2013 and Gonzalez-Coloma et al 2013 the Gonzalez-Coloma group discovered a chemotype that does not produce β-thujone but does contain terpenoids not seen elsewhere.
[src:beer/absinth-wormwood] It is an ingredient in the spirit absinthe, and is used for flavouring in some other spirits and wines, including bitters, bäsk, vermouth, and pelinkovac.
[src:beer/absinth-wormwood] As a folk medicine, it is claimed to counteract poor appetite and to treat various diseases such as Crohn's disease and IgA nephropathy.
[src:beer/absinth-wormwood] Wormwood was traditionally relatively common as a bittering spice in farmhouse brewing in Denmark, and to some extent Estonia.
[src:beer/absinth-wormwood] In 18th-century England, wormwood was sometimes used instead of hops in beer.
[src:beer/absinth-wormwood] According to Nicholas Culpeper, a stinking breath can be cured by "drinking a glass of Wormwood beer every morning".
[src:beer/absinth-wormwood] Historical sources describe the use of *Artemisia absinthium* as an anthelmintic and antiprotozoal remedy, with modern studies reporting antibacterial, antifungal, and antibiofilm activity of its extracts.
[src:beer/absinth-wormwood] Wormwood-based alcoholic preparations, including absinthe, were also prescribed as prophylaxis during the 19th-century French conquest of Algeria.
[src:beer/absinth-wormwood] Wormwood clippings and cuttings are added to chicken nesting boxes to repel lice, mites, and fleas.
[src:beer/absinth-wormwood] Bailen *et al.* 2013 and Gonzalez-Coloma *et al.* 2013 find the unique terpenoids of the Gonzalez-Coloma chemotype make this strain especially promising for insect control.
[src:beer/absinth-wormwood] As of 2020 a company named EcoflorAgro is investing heavily into increasing the planted area of this strain, hoping to commercialize it to a degree attempted – but never achieved due to unreliable supply – for other botanical insecticides before.
[src:beer/absinth-wormwood] Most chemotypes of *A. absinthium* contain (−)-α- and/or (+)-β-thujone, though some do not.
[src:beer/absinth-wormwood] (−)-α-Thujone by itself is a GABAA receptor antagonist that can cause convulsions when administered in large amounts to animals and humans.
[src:beer/absinth-wormwood] However, there is only one case of documented toxicity of wormwood, in which a 31-year-old man drank 10 mL of steam-distilled pure volatile oil of wormwood, wrongly believing it was absinthe liqueur.
[src:beer/absinth-wormwood] Medicinal extracts of wormwood have not been shown to cause seizures or other adverse effects at usual doses.
[src:beer/absinth-wormwood] Thujones have not been shown to be the cause of excessive doses' toxicity for any kind of wormwood extracts, including absinthe.
[src:beer/absinth-wormwood] In the apocalyptic Book of Revelation ending the Bible, the star named "Wormwood" falls to earth and turns a third of its waters bitter.
[src:beer/absinth-wormwood] Similarly where the Biblical Hebrew word לענה (*la'anah*) appears in the Hebrew Bible, it is generally translated into English as "wormwood".
[src:beer/absinth-wormwood] The word occurs nine times in the Hebrew Bible, seven times with the implication of bitterness and twice as a proper noun, in the Greek translation *apsinthos*, naming the physical meteor in its orbit, in Revelation 8:11.
[src:beer/absinth-wormwood] The English rendering "wormwood" additionally refers to the dark green oil produced by the plant, which was used to kill intestinal worms.
[src:beer/absinth-wormwood] The Ukrainian city Chernobyl, notable for its catastrophic nuclear disaster in 1986, is named from one of the Ukrainian names for common wormwood: чорнобиль, *chornóbyl'* (or more commonly полин звичайний *polýn zvycháynyy*, 'common artemisia').
[src:beer/absinth-wormwood] The name is inherited from Proto-Slavic *čьrnobylъ or *čьrnobyl, a compound of *čьrnъ, 'black' + *bylь, 'grass', the parts related to Ukrainian: чорний, romanized: *chórnyy*, lit.
[src:beer/absinth-wormwood] 'black' and било *byló*, 'stalk', which may also refer to *A. vulgaris*.
[src:beer/absinth-wormwood] Lucretius, reflecting on life in the Roman Republic before 50 BCE, stated in his poem De rerum natura that, "Physicians, when they wish to treat children with a nasty dose of wormwood, first smear the rim of the cup with a sweet coat of yellow honey.
[src:beer/absinth-wormwood] The children, too young as yet for foresight, are lured by the sweetness at their lips into swallowing the bitter draught.
[src:beer/absinth-wormwood] Nicholas Culpeper insisted that wormwood was the key to understanding his 1651 book *The English Physitian*.
[src:beer/absinth-wormwood] Richard Mabey describes Culpeper's entry on this bitter-tasting plant as "stream-of-consciousness" and "unlike anything else in the herbal", and states that it reads "like the ramblings of a drunk".
[src:beer/absinth-wormwood] Culpeper biographer Benjamin Woolley suggests the piece may be an allegory about bitterness, as Culpeper had spent his life fighting the Establishment, and had been imprisoned and seriously wounded in battle as a result.
[src:beer/absinth-wormwood] William Shakespeare referred to wormwood in *Romeo and Juliet*: Act 1, Scene 3.
[src:beer/absinth-wormwood] Juliet's childhood nurse said, "For I had then laid wormwood to my dug" meaning that the nurse had weaned Juliet, then aged three, by using the bitter taste of wormwood on her nipple.
[src:beer/absinth-wormwood] He also referred to wormwood in *Hamlet*: Act 3, Scene 2.
[src:beer/absinth-wormwood] Hamlet said, "That's wormwood" in response to the Player Queen expressing distaste for remarriage.
[src:beer/absinth-wormwood] Edwin Arlington Robinson relates in a poem how Cliff Klingenhagen gave a guest a glass of wine while drinking a glass of wormwood himself.
[src:beer/beer] Beer is distributed in bottles and cans, and is commonly available on draught in pubs and bars.
[src:beer/beer] The brewing industry is a global business, consisting of several dominant multinational corporations and many thousands of smaller producers ranging from brewpubs to regional breweries.
[src:beer/beer] The strength of modern beer is usually around 4% to 6% alcohol by volume (ABV).
[src:beer/beer] Some of the earliest writings mention the production and distribution of beer: the Code of Hammurabi (1750 BC) included laws regulating it, while "The Hymn to Ninkasi", a prayer to the Mesopotamian goddess of beer, contains a recipe for it.
[src:beer/beer] Beer forms part of the culture of many nations and is associated with social traditions such as beer festivals, as well as activities like pub games.
[src:beer/beer] Beer can cause health issues if consumed often or in excess; alcohol is an IARC group 1 carcinogen.
[src:beer/beer] In early forms of English and in the Scandinavian languages, the usual word for beer was the word whose Modern English form is *ale*.
[src:beer/beer] The modern word *beer* comes into present-day English from Old English *bēor*, itself from Proto-Germanic; it is found throughout the West Germanic and North Germanic dialects (modern Dutch and German *bier*, Old Norse *bjórr*).
[src:beer/beer] Christine Fell, in *Leeds Studies in English* (1975), suggests that the Old English/Norse word *bēor* did not originally denote ale or beer, but a strong, sweet drink rather like mead or cider.
[src:beer/beer] Whatever the case, the meaning of *bēor* expanded to cover the meaning of 'ale'.
[src:beer/beer] When hopped ale from Europe was imported into Britain in the late Middle Ages, it was described as "beer" to differentiate it from the British unhopped ale, later acquiring a broader meaning.
[src:beer/beer] Beer is one of the world's oldest prepared alcoholic drinks.
[src:beer/beer] The earliest archaeological evidence of fermentation consists of 13,000 year-old residues of a beer with the consistency of gruel, used by the semi-nomadic Natufians for ritual feasting, at the Raqefet Cave in the Carmel Mountains near Haifa in northern Israel.
[src:beer/beer] There is evidence that beer was produced at Göbekli Tepe during the Pre-Pottery Neolithic (around 8500 BC to 5500 BC).
[src:beer/beer] The earliest clear chemical evidence of beer produced from barley dates to about 3500–3100 BC, from the site of Godin Tepe in the Zagros Mountains of western Iran.
[src:beer/beer] Beer is recorded in the written history of ancient Egypt, and archaeologists speculate that beer was instrumental in the formation of civilisations.
[src:beer/beer] The Sumerians drank a variety of beers, eight types from barley, 12 types from wheat and 3 from a mixture of grains.
[src:beer/beer] The Sumerian goddess Ninkasi was believed to oversee the brewing process, and the production and distribution of beer was attributed there to women.
[src:beer/beer] Approximately 5000 years ago, workers in the city of Uruk (modern day Iraq) were paid by their employers with volumes of beer.
[src:beer/beer] During the building of the Egyptian pyramids, each worker got a daily ration of four to five litres of beer, which served as both nutrition and refreshment and was crucial to the pyramids' construction.
[src:beer/beer] Day and night make merry") to Gilgamesh, recorded in the *Epic of Gilgamesh* by the alewife Siduri, may, at least in part, have referred to the consumption of beer.
[src:beer/beer] The Ebla tablets, discovered in 1974 in Ebla, Syria, show that beer was produced in the city in 2500 BC.
[src:beer/beer] A fermented drink using rice and fruit was made in China around 7000 BC.
[src:beer/beer] Unlike sake, mould was not used to saccharify the rice (amylolytic fermentation); the rice was probably prepared for fermentation by chewing or malting.
[src:beer/beer] During the Vedic period in Ancient India, there are records of the consumption of the beer-like *sura*.
[src:beer/beer] 4th century BCE Greek philosopher Xenophon noted that during his travels, "barley wine" was being produced in Armenia and drunk through straws.
[src:beer/beer] Beer was spread through Europe by Germanic and Celtic tribes as far back as 3000 BC, and it was mainly brewed on a domestic scale.
[src:beer/beer] The product that the early Europeans drank might not be recognised as beer by most people today.
[src:beer/beer] Alongside the basic starch source, the early European beers may have contained fruits, honey, numerous types of plants, spices, and other substances such as narcotic herbs.
[src:beer/beer] This mixture was called gruit, where if some were improperly heated could cause hallucinations.
[src:beer/beer] The mixture of gruit was different from every brewer.
[src:beer/beer] What they did not contain was hops, as that was a later addition, first mentioned in Europe around 822 by a Carolingian Abbot and again in the twelfth century by abbess Hildegard of Bingen.
[src:beer/beer] In 1516, William IV, Duke of Bavaria adopted the *Reinheitsgebot* (purity law), perhaps the oldest food-quality regulation still in use in the 21st century, according to which the only allowed ingredients of beer are water, hops, and barley-malt.
[src:beer/beer] Beer produced before the Industrial Revolution was made and sold on a domestic scale, although by the 7th century AD, beer was also being produced and sold by European monasteries.
[src:beer/beer] During the Industrial Revolution, the production of beer moved from artisanal to industrial manufacture, while domestic production ceased to be significant by the end of the 19th century.
[src:beer/beer] In 1912, brown bottles began to be used by the Joseph Schlitz Brewing Company of Milwaukee, Wisconsin, in the United States.
[src:beer/beer] This innovation has since been accepted worldwide as it prevents light rays from degrading the quality and stability of beer.
[src:beer/beer] The brewing industry is a global business, consisting of several dominant multinational companies and many thousands of smaller producers, ranging from brewpubs to regional breweries.
[src:beer/beer] As of 2006, more than 133 billion litres (35 billion US gallons) of beer are sold per year, producing global revenues of US$294.5 billion.
[src:beer/beer] In 2010, China's beer consumption hit 450 billion litres (120 billion US gallons), or nearly twice that of the United States, but only 5 per cent sold were premium beers, compared with 50 per cent in France and Germany.
[src:beer/beer] Beer is the most widely consumed of all alcoholic drinks.
[src:beer/beer] A widely publicised study in 2018 suggested that sudden decreases in barley production due to extreme drought and heat could in the future cause substantial volatility in the availability and price of beer.
[src:beer/beer] It converts the grain into a sugary liquid called wort and then ferments this into beer using yeast.
[src:beer/beer] The first step, mixing malted barley with hot water in a mash tun, is "mashing".
[src:beer/beer] The starches are converted to sugars, and the sweet wort is drained off.
[src:beer/beer] The grains are washed to extract as much fermentable liquid from the grains as possible.
[src:beer/beer] The sweet wort is put into a kettle, or "copper", and boiled.
[src:beer/beer] Hops are added as a source of bitterness, flavour, and aroma.
[src:beer/beer] The longer the hops are boiled, the more bitterness they contribute, but the less hop flavour and aroma remain.
[src:beer/beer] The wort is cooled and the yeast is added.
[src:beer/beer] The wort is then fermented, often for a week or longer.
[src:beer/beer] The yeast settles, leaving the beer clear.
[src:beer/beer] During fermentation, most of the carbon dioxide is allowed to escape through a trap.
[src:beer/beer] The carbonation is often increased either by transferring the beer to a pressure vessel and introducing pressurised carbon dioxide or by transferring it before the fermentation is finished so that carbon dioxide pressure builds up inside the container.
[src:beer/beer] The basic ingredients of beer are water; a starch source, usually malted barley; a brewer's yeast to produce the fermentation; and a flavouring such as hops.
[src:beer/beer] A mixture of starch sources may be used, with a secondary carbohydrate source, such as maize (corn), rice, wheat, or sugar, often termed an adjunct, especially when used alongside malted barley.
[src:beer/beer] Less widely used starch sources include millet, sorghum, and cassava root in Africa; potato in Brazil; and agave in Mexico.
[src:beer/beer] Water is the main ingredient, accounting for 93% of beer's weight.
[src:beer/beer] The level of dissolved bicarbonate influences beer's finished taste.
[src:beer/beer] Due to the mineral properties of each region's water, specific areas were originally the sole producers of certain types of beer, each identifiable by regional characteristics.
[src:beer/beer] Dublin's hard water is well-suited to making stout, such as Guinness, while the Plzeň Region's soft water is ideal for brewing Pilsner, such as Pilsner Urquell.
[src:beer/beer] The waters of Burton in England contain gypsum, which benefits making pale ale to such a degree that brewers of pale ale add gypsum in a process known as Burtonisation.
[src:beer/beer] The starch source provides the fermentable material and determines the strength and flavour of the beer.
[src:beer/beer] The most common starch source used in beer is malted grain.
[src:beer/beer] Grain is malted by soaking it in water, allowing it to begin germination, and then drying the partially germinated grain in a kiln.
[src:beer/beer] Malting produces enzymes that convert starches into fermentable sugars.
[src:beer/beer] Different roasting times and temperatures produce different colours of malt from the same grain.
[src:beer/beer] Nearly all beers use barley malt for most of the starch, as its fibrous hull remains attached to the grain during threshing.
[src:beer/beer] After malting, barley is milled, which finally removes the hull, breaking it into large pieces.
[src:beer/beer] These pieces remain with the grain during the mash and act as a filter bed during lautering, when sweet wort is separated from insoluble grain material.
[src:beer/beer] Other grains, including wheat, rice, oats, and rye, and less frequently, corn and sorghum may be used.
[src:beer/beer] Some brewers have produced gluten-free beer, made with sorghum, for those who cannot consume gluten-containing grains like wheat, barley, and rye.
[src:beer/beer] Flavouring beer is the sole commercial use of hops.
[src:beer/beer] The flower of the hop vine acts as a flavouring and preservative agent in nearly all beer made today.
[src:beer/beer] The flowers themselves are often called "hops".
[src:beer/beer] The first historical mention of the use of hops in beer dates from 822 AD in monastery rules written by Adalard of Corbie, though widespread cultivation of hops for use in beer began in the thirteenth century.
[src:beer/beer] Before then, beer was flavoured with other plants such as grains of paradise or 'alehoof'.
[src:beer/beer] Combinations of aromatic herbs, berries, and even wormwood were combined into a flavouring mixture known as gruit.
[src:beer/beer] Hops contribute a bitterness that balances the sweetness of the malt; the bitterness of beers is measured on the International Bitterness Units scale.
[src:beer/beer] Hops further contribute floral, citrus, and herbal aromas and flavours.
[src:beer/beer] They have an antibiotic effect that favours the activity of brewer's yeast over less desirable microorganisms, and aids in "head retention", the length of time that a foamy head created by carbonation will last.
[src:beer/beer] Yeast is the microorganism responsible for fermenting beer.
[src:beer/beer] It metabolises the sugars, producing ethanol and carbon dioxide, and thereby turns wort into beer.
[src:beer/beer] In addition, yeast influences the character and flavour.
[src:beer/beer] The dominant types of beer yeast are top-fermenting *Saccharomyces cerevisiae* and bottom-fermenting *Saccharomyces pastorianus*.
[src:beer/beer] *Brettanomyces* ferments lambics, and *Torulaspora delbrueckii* ferments Bavarian weissbier.
[src:beer/beer] Before the role of yeast in fermentation was understood, fermentation involved wild or airborne yeasts.
[src:beer/beer] A few styles, such as lambics, rely on this method today, but most modern fermentation adds pure yeast cultures.
[src:beer/beer] Some brewers add clarifying agents or finings to beer, which typically precipitate (collect as a solid) out along with protein solids, and are found only in trace amounts in the finished product.
[src:beer/beer] This process makes the beer appear bright and clean, rather than the cloudy appearance of ethnic and older styles such as wheat beers.
[src:beer/beer] Clarifying agents include isinglass, from the swimbladders of fish; Irish moss, a seaweed; kappa carrageenan, from the seaweed *Kappaphycus cottonii*; Polyclar (artificial); and gelatin.
[src:beer/beer] Beer marked "suitable for vegans" is clarified either with seaweed or with artificial agents.
[src:beer/beer] In the 21st century, larger breweries have repeatedly taken over smaller breweries.
[src:beer/beer] In 2002, South African Breweries bought the North American Miller Brewing Company to found SABMiller, becoming the second-largest brewery after North American Anheuser-Busch.
[src:beer/beer] In 2004, the Belgian Interbrew was the third-largest brewery by volume, and the Brazilian AmBev was the fifth-largest.
[src:beer/beer] They merged into InBev, becoming the largest brewery.
[src:beer/beer] In 2007, SABMiller surpassed InBev and Anheuser-Busch when it acquired Royal Grolsch, the brewer of Dutch brand Grolsch.
[src:beer/beer] In 2008, when InBev (the second-largest) bought Anheuser-Busch (the third-largest), the new Anheuser-Busch InBev company became again the largest brewer in the world.
[src:beer/beer] As of 2020, according to the market research firm Technavio, AB InBev was the largest brewing company in the world, with Heineken second, CR Snow third, Carlsberg fourth, and Molson Coors fifth.
[src:beer/beer] A *microbrewery*, or *craft brewery*, produces a limited amount of beer.
[src:beer/beer] The maximum amount of beer a brewery can produce and still be classed as a 'microbrewery' varies by region and by authority; in the US, it is 15,000 US beer barrels (1.8 megalitres; 390 thousand imperial gallons; 460 thousand US gallons) a year.
[src:beer/beer] A *brewpub* is a type of microbrewery that incorporates a pub or other drinking establishment.
[src:beer/beer] The highest density of breweries in the world, most of them microbreweries, exists in Franconia, Germany, especially in the district of Upper Franconia, which has about 200 breweries.
[src:beer/beer] The Benedictine Weihenstephan brewery in Bavaria, Germany, can trace its roots to the year 768, as a document from that year refers to a hop garden in the area paying a tithe to the monastery.
[src:beer/beer] It claims to be the oldest working brewery in the world.
[src:beer/beer] Top-fermented beers are most commonly produced with *Saccharomyces cerevisiae*, a top-fermenting yeast which clumps and rises to the surface, typically between 15 and 25 °C (59 and 77 °F).
[src:beer/beer] At these temperatures, yeast produces significant amounts of esters and other secondary flavour and aroma products, and the result is often a beer with slightly "fruity" compounds resembling apple, pear, pineapple, banana, plum, or prune, among others.
[src:beer/beer] After the introduction of hops into England from Flanders in the 15th century, "ale" came to mean an unhopped fermented brew, while "beer" meant a brew with an infusion of hops.
[src:beer/beer] The term 'real ale' was coined by the Campaign for Real Ale (CAMRA) in 1973 for "beer brewed from traditional ingredients, matured by secondary fermentation in the container from which it is dispensed, and served without the use of extraneous carbon dioxide".
[src:beer/beer] It is applied to both bottle conditioned and cask conditioned beers.
[src:beer/beer] As for the types of top-fermented beers, pale ale predominantly uses pale malt.
[src:beer/beer] It is one of the world's major beer styles and includes India pale ale (IPA).
[src:beer/beer] Mild ale has a predominantly malty palate.
[src:beer/beer] It is usually dark, with an abv of 3% to 3.6%.
[src:beer/beer] Wheat beer is brewed with a large proportion of wheat although it often also contains a significant proportion of malted barley.
[src:beer/beer] Stout is a dark beer made using roasted barley, and typically brewed with slow fermenting yeast.
[src:beer/beer] There are a number of variations including dry stout (such as Guinness), sweet stout, and Imperial (or Russian) stout.
[src:beer/beer] Stout was originally the strongest variety of porter, a dark brown beer popular with the street and river porters of eighteenth century London.
[src:beer/beer] Pale lagers are the most commonly drunk beers in the world.
[src:beer/beer] The name "lager" comes from the German "lagern" for "to store", as brewers in Bavaria stored beer in cool cellars during the warm summer months, allowing the beers to continue to ferment, and to clear any sediment.
[src:beer/beer] Lager yeast is a cool bottom-fermenting yeast (*Saccharomyces pastorianus*).
[src:beer/beer] Lager typically undergoes primary fermentation at 7–12 °C (45–54 °F), and then a long secondary fermentation at 0–4 °C (32–39 °F) (the lagering phase).
[src:beer/beer] During the secondary stage, the lager clears and mellows.
[src:beer/beer] The cooler conditions inhibit the natural production of esters and other byproducts, resulting in a "cleaner"-tasting beer.
[src:beer/beer] With improved modern yeast strains, most lager breweries use only short periods of cold storage, typically no more than 2 weeks.
[src:beer/beer] Some traditional lagers are still stored for several months.
[src:beer/beer] Lambic, a beer of Belgium, is naturally fermented using wild yeasts, rather than cultivated.
[src:beer/beer] Many of these are not strains of brewer's yeast (*Saccharomyces cerevisiae*) and may have significant differences in aroma and sourness.
[src:beer/beer] Yeast varieties such as *Brettanomyces bruxellensis* and *Brettanomyces lambicus* are common in lambics.
[src:beer/beer] In addition, other organisms such as *Lactobacillus* bacteria produce acids which contribute to the sourness.
[src:beer/beer] Around the world, many traditional and ancient starch-based drinks are classed as beer.
[src:beer/beer] In Africa, there are ethnic beers made from sorghum or millet, such as Oshikundu in Namibia and Tella in Ethiopia.
[src:beer/beer] Kyrgyzstan also has a beer made from millet; it is a low alcohol, somewhat porridge-like drink called "Bozo".
[src:beer/beer] Bhutan, Nepal, Tibet and Sikkim also use millet in Chhaang, a popular semi-fermented rice/millet drink in the eastern Himalayas.
[src:beer/beer] Beers made from bread, among the earliest forms of the drink, are Sahti in Finland, Kvass in Russia and Ukraine, and Bouza in Sudan.
[src:beer/beer] 4000 years ago fermented bread was used in Mesopotamia.
[src:beer/beer] Food waste activists got inspired by these ancient recipes and use leftover bread to replace a third of the malted barley that would otherwise be used for brewing their craft ale.
[src:beer/beer] Beer is measured and assessed by colour, by strength and by bitterness.
[src:beer/beer] The strength of modern beer is usually around 4% to 6%, measured as alcohol by volume (ABV).
[src:beer/beer] The perceived bitterness is measured by the International Bitterness Units scale (IBU), defined in co-operation between the American Society of Brewing Chemists and the European Brewery Convention.
[src:beer/beer] The international scale was a development of the European Bitterness Units scale, often abbreviated as EBU, and the bitterness values should be identical.
[src:beer/beer] The most common colour is a pale amber produced from using pale malts.
[src:beer/beer] *Pale lager* and *pale ale* are terms used for beers made from malt dried and roasted with the fuel coke.
[src:beer/beer] Coke was first used for roasting malt in 1642, but it was not until around 1703 that the term *pale ale* was used.
[src:beer/beer] In terms of sales volume, most of today's beer is based on the pale lager brewed in 1842 in the city of Plzeň in the present-day Czech Republic.
[src:beer/beer] The modern pale lager is light in colour due to use of coke for kilning, which gives off heat with little smoke.
[src:beer/beer] Dark beers are usually brewed from a pale malt or lager malt base with a small proportion of darker malt added to achieve the desired shade.
[src:beer/beer] Other colourants—such as caramel—are also widely used to darken beers.
[src:beer/beer] Very dark beers, such as stout, use dark or patent malts that have been roasted longer.
[src:beer/beer] Beer ranges from less than 3% alcohol by volume (abv) to around 14% abv, though this strength can be increased to around 20% by re-pitching with champagne yeast, and to 55% ABV by the freeze-distilling process.
[src:beer/beer] The alcohol content of beer varies by local practice or beer style.
[src:beer/beer] The pale lagers that most consumers are familiar with fall in the range of 4–6%, with a typical ABV of 5%.
[src:beer/beer] The customary strength of British ales is quite low, with many session beers being around 4% abv.
[src:beer/beer] In Belgium, some beers, such as table beer are of such low alcohol content (1%–4%) that they are served instead of soft drinks in some schools.
[src:beer/beer] The weakest beers are described as 'alcohol-free', typically containing 0.05% ABV; this compares to low alcohol beers which may contain 1.2% ABV or less, and conventional beers which average 4.4% ABV.
[src:beer/beer] The strength of beers has climbed during the later years of the 20th century.
[src:beer/beer] Since then, some brewers have used champagne yeasts to increase the alcohol content of their beers.
[src:beer/beer] Samuel Adams reached 20% ABV with *Millennium*, and then surpassed that amount to 25.6% ABV with Utopias.
[src:beer/beer] The strongest beer brewed in Britain was Baz's Super Brew by Parish Brewery, a 23% ABV beer.
[src:beer/beer] In September 2011, the Scottish brewery BrewDog produced Ghost Deer, which, at 28%, they claim to be the world's strongest beer produced by fermentation alone.
[src:beer/beer] The product claimed to be the strongest beer made is Schorschbräu's 2011 *Schorschbock 57* with 57.5% ABV.
[src:beer/beer] It was preceded by *The End of History*, a 55% Belgian ale, made by BrewDog in 2010.
[src:beer/beer] The same company had previously made *Sink The Bismarck!*, a 41% ABV IPA, and *Tactical Nuclear Penguin*, a 32% ABV Imperial stout.
[src:beer/beer] Each of these beers are made using the eisbock method of fractional freezing, in which a strong ale is partially frozen and the ice is repeatedly removed, until the desired strength is reached, a process that may class the product as spirits rather than beer.
[src:beer/beer] The German brewery Schorschbräu's *Schorschbock*, a 31% ABV eisbock, and Hair of the Dog's *Dave*, a 29% ABV barley wine made in 1994, used the same fractional freezing method.
[src:beer/beer] A 60% ABV blend of beer with whiskey was jokingly claimed as the strongest beer by a Dutch brewery in July 2010.
[src:beer/beer] Draught (also spelt "draft") beer from a pressurised keg using a lever-style dispenser and a spout is the most common method of dispensing in bars around the world.
[src:beer/beer] A metal keg is pressurised with carbon dioxide (CO2) gas which drives the beer to the dispensing tap or faucet.
[src:beer/beer] Some beers may be served with a nitrogen/carbon dioxide mixture.
[src:beer/beer] Nitrogen produces fine bubbles, resulting in a dense head and a creamy mouthfeel.
[src:beer/beer] In the 1980s, Guinness introduced the beer widget, a nitrogen-pressurised ball inside a can which creates a moderately dense, tight head.
[src:beer/beer] This approximates the effect of serving from a keg, at least for a British-style beer which does not have a specially large head.
[src:beer/beer] Cask-conditioned ales (or cask ales) are unfiltered and unpasteurised beers.
[src:beer/beer] These beers are termed "real ale" by the CAMRA organisation.
[src:beer/beer] The act of stillaging and then venting a beer in this manner typically disturbs all the sediment, so it must be left for a suitable period of hours to days to "drop" (clear) again, as well as to fully condition the beer.
[src:beer/beer] At this point the beer is ready to sell, either being pulled through a beer line with a hand pump, or simply being "gravity-fed" directly into the glass.
[src:beer/beer] Draught beer's environmental impact can be 68% lower than bottled beer due to packaging differences.
[src:beer/beer] A life cycle study of one beer brand, including grain production, brewing, bottling, distribution and waste management, shows that the CO2 emissions from a 6-pack of micro-brew beer is about 3 kilograms (6.6 pounds).
[src:beer/beer] The loss of natural habitat potential from the 6-pack of micro-brew beer is estimated to be 2.5 square metres (26 square feet).
[src:beer/beer] Downstream emissions from distribution, retail, storage and disposal of waste can be over 45% of a bottled micro-brew beer's CO2 emissions.
[src:beer/beer] Where legal, the use of a refillable jug, reusable bottle or other reusable containers to transport draught beer from a store or a bar, rather than buying pre-bottled beer, can reduce the environmental impact of beer consumption.
[src:beer/beer] Most beers are cleared of yeast by filtering when packaged in bottles and cans.
[src:beer/beer] However, bottle conditioned beers retain some yeast—either by being unfiltered, or by being filtered and then reseeded with fresh yeast.
[src:beer/beer] Many beers are sold in cans, though there is considerable variation in the proportion between different countries.
[src:beer/beer] In Sweden in 2001, 63.9% of beer was sold in cans.
[src:beer/beer] People either drink from the can or pour the beer into a glass.
[src:beer/beer] A technology developed by Crown Holdings for the 2010 FIFA World Cup is the 'full aperture' can, so named because the entire lid is removed during the opening process, turning the can into a drinking cup.
[src:beer/beer] Cans protect the beer from light (thereby preventing spoilage) and have a seal less prone to leaking over time than bottles.
[src:beer/beer] Cans were initially viewed as a technological breakthrough for maintaining the quality of a beer, then became commonly associated with less expensive, mass-produced beers, even though the quality of storage in cans is much like bottles.
[src:beer/beer] Plastic (PET) bottles are used by some breweries.
[src:beer/beer] The temperature of a beer has an influence on a drinker's experience; warmer temperatures reveal the range of flavours in a beer but cooler temperatures are more refreshing.
[src:beer/beer] Most drinkers prefer pale lager to be served chilled, a low- or medium-strength pale ale to be served cool, while a strong barley wine or imperial stout to be served at room temperature.
[src:beer/beer] Drinking chilled beer began with the development of artificial refrigeration and by the 1870s, was spread in those countries that concentrated on brewing pale lager.
[src:beer/beer] Chilling beer makes it more refreshing, though below 15.5 °C (60 °F) the chilling starts to reduce taste awareness and reduces it significantly below 10 °C (50 °F).
[src:beer/beer] Beer served unchilled—either cool or at room temperature—reveal more of their flavours.
[src:beer/beer] Cask Marque, a non-profit UK beer organisation, has set a temperature standard range of 12°–14 °C (53°–57 °F) for cask ales to be served.
[src:beer/beer] Beer is consumed out of a variety of vessels, such as a glass, a beer stein, a mug, a pewter tankard, a beer bottle or a can; or at music festivals and some bars and nightclubs, from a plastic cup.
[src:beer/beer] The shape of the glass from which beer is consumed can influence the perception of the beer and can define and accent the character of the style.
[src:beer/beer] Breweries offer branded glassware intended only for their own beers as a marketing promotion, as this increases sales of their product.
[src:beer/beer] The pouring process has an influence on a beer's presentation.
[src:beer/beer] A beer tower or portable beer tap is sometimes used in bars and restaurants to allow a group of customers to serve themselves.
[src:beer/beer] The device consists of a tall container with a cooling mechanism and a beer tap at its base.
[src:beer/beer] Beer contains the phenolic acids 4-hydroxyphenylacetic acid, vanillic acid, caffeic acid, syringic acid, *p*-coumaric acid, ferulic acid, and sinapic acid.
[src:beer/beer] Alkaline hydrolysis experiments show that most of the phenolic acids are present as bound forms and only a small portion can be detected as free compounds.
[src:beer/beer] Hops, and beer made with it, contain 8-prenylnaringenin which is a potent phytoestrogen.
[src:beer/beer] Hop also contains myrcene, humulene, xanthohumol, isoxanthohumol, myrcenol, linalool, tannins, and resin.
[src:beer/beer] The alcohol 2M2B is a component of hops brewing.
[src:beer/beer] Barley, in the form of malt, brings the condensed tannins prodelphinidins B3, B9 and C2 into beer.
[src:beer/beer] Beers vary in their nutritional content.
[src:beer/beer] The ingredients used to make beer, including the yeast, provide a rich source of nutrients; therefore beer may contain nutrients including magnesium, selenium, potassium, phosphorus, biotin, chromium and B vitamins.
[src:beer/beer] Beer is sometimes referred to as "liquid bread", though beer is not a meal in itself.
[src:beer/beer] A 2018 systematic analysis found that ethanol consumption increases mortality rate.
[src:beer/beer] Alcohol use is the third leading cause of early deaths in the United States.
[src:beer/beer] In the United States, a total of 88,000 deaths per year (5.9% of all deaths) are believed to be due to alcohol.
[src:beer/beer] No professional medical association recommends that people who are nondrinkers should start drinking alcoholic beverages.
[src:beer/beer] The long-term health effects of continuous, moderate or heavy alcohol consumption include the risk of developing alcoholism and alcoholic liver disease.
[src:beer/beer] In addition, like all alcoholic drinks, it is an IARC group 1 carcinogen.
[src:beer/beer] Alcoholism, also known as "alcohol use disorder", is a broad term for any drinking of alcohol that results in problems.
[src:beer/beer] It was previously divided into two types: alcohol abuse and alcohol dependence.
[src:beer/beer] Alcoholism reduces a person's life expectancy by around ten years.
[src:beer/beer] Overeating and lack of muscle tone is the main cause of a beer belly, rather than beer consumption, though a 2004 study found a link between binge drinking and a beer belly.
[src:beer/beer] Some diet books in the past suggested that beer has an undesirably high glycemic index of 110, the same as maltose; however, the maltose in beer is metabolised by yeast during fermentation, thus beer consists mostly of water, hop oils and only trace amounts of sugars, including maltose.
[src:beer/beer] The multi-step process of beer production is effective at removing pesticide residues from grain.
[src:beer/beer] At each step (e.g. mashing or malting) pesticide levels are typically reduced by 50-90%, varying with the particular process and pesticide's chemical properties.
[src:beer/beer] Some of the earliest writings mention the production and distribution of beer: the c.
[src:beer/beer] 1750 BC Babylonian Code of Hammurabi included laws regulating it, while "The Hymn to Ninkasi", a c.
[src:beer/beer] 1800 BC prayer to the Mesopotamian goddess of beer, a recipe for it.
[src:beer/beer] In many societies, beer is the most popular alcoholic drink.
[src:beer/beer] Various social traditions and activities are associated with beer drinking, such as playing cards, darts, or other pub games; attending beer festivals; engaging in zythology (the study of beer); visiting a series of pubs in one evening; visiting breweries; beer-oriented tourism; or rating beer.
[src:beer/beer] Drinking games, such as beer pong, accompany the drinking of beer.
[src:beer/beer] Even having a "shower beer" has developed a following.
[src:beer/beer] A relatively new profession is that of the beer sommelier, who informs restaurant patrons about beers and food pairings.
[src:beer/beer] Some breweries have developed beers to pair with food.
[src:beer/beer] Wine writer Malcolm Gluck disputed the need to pair beer with food, while beer writers Roger Protz and Melissa Cole contested that claim.
[src:beer/beer] Beer is considered to be a social lubricant, and is consumed in countries all over the world.
[src:beer/beer] There are breweries in Middle Eastern countries such as Syria, and in some African countries.
[src:beer/beer] Sales of beer are four times those of wine, which is the second most popular alcoholic drink.
